.TH encase 3
.XI encase - "Encase a text region with start/end string"
.SH NAME
encase \- Encase a text region with start/end string
.Me $a
.SH SYNOPSIS
.na
.Me "|encase"
.B encase
"\|\fIstart-string\fR\|"
"\|\fIend-string\fR\|"
.ad
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B encase
provides  a  short  cut to  encapsulate  a  selected  region  of  text  with a
\fIstart-string\fR  and  \fIend-string\fR  pattern.  The  command is modal and
operates in two different operating modes as follows.
.PP
First run
.B encase
without a current region section (i.e. no selected  highlighted  text) and the
user is prompted for the  \fIstart-string\fR and \fIend-string\fR. The user is
also   prompted   if  the   command   has  not   been  run   before   and  the
\fIstart-string\fR  and  \fIend-string\fR  are  undefined.
.PP
With the  strings  defined  then  select a region  with the mouse or  keyboard
(\fB\*espace\fR  and \fBmove\fR or  \fB\*smove\fR) to define the start and end
point of the region. With a selected region then execute the
.B encase
command using \fB\*ex\fR  \fBencase\fR. This is most effective when bound to a
simple key, see
.Ht global-bind-key 2 .
.SH NOTES
.B encase 
is a macro defined in \fCmisc.emf\fR.
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.na
